[[Brigadier General]] '''Gul Aqa Nahib''' (also, "Nahibi", "Naebi", or simply "Gul Aqa") of the [[Afghan National Army]] served as second-in-command to transitional Defence Minister [[Mohammed Fahim]] in 2002<ref name="iwpr">[http://iwpr.net/?p=arr&s=f&o=154307&apc_state=heniarr2002 Concern Over Tajik "Control" of New Army<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and is currently in charge of 12,000 troops overseeing operations in [[Kandahar]].<ref>[http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/LAC.20071025.AFGHANANA25/TPStory/TPInternational/Asia/ globeandmail.com: World<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
He joined the army in 1965<ref>[http://ipsnews.net/wap/news.asp?idnews=39647 IPS - Inter Press Service<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
His formal position is as commander of the [[205th Corps|Afghan 205th Corps]], based out of [[Kandahar Airport]],<ref name="rferl.org">[http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2007/09/651f2159-7d5d-4921-8ba8-0ab76e8b0420.html Afghanistan: National Army Short Of Everything But Spirit - RADIO FREE EUROPE / RADIO LIBERTY<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and he is in charge of operations for Southern Afghanistan.
On September 9 2007, he reported that insurgent forces were no longer able to beat ANA troops in combat.<ref name="rferl.org"/>
He speaks [[Dari (Afghanistan)|Dari]], in addition to his native [[Pashto language|Pashto]]<ref>[http://www.europeanvoice.com/archive/article.asp?id=28934 Afghanistanâ€™s weakest link<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and supports the idea of [[conscription]].<ref name="iwpr" />
